[1] Cholera - Uganda (Hoima, Kibaale, Bundibugyo)
Date: Fri, 2 Jun 2006
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: African News Dimension [edited]
<http://health.andnetwork.com/index?service=direct/1/Home/recent.titleStory&sp=l37185>

A total of 23 people in the districts of Hoima, Kibaale and
Bundibugyo in Uganda have died following a cholera outbreak.
Addressing journalists in Hoima on 26 May 2006, the District Director
of Health Services, Dr Joseph Ruyonga, said the epidemic had been
confirmed in the sub-counties of Kyangwali, Kabwooya, Buseruka and
Kigorobya.
"The disease has so far killed 10 people in the villages of Nyawaiga,
Buhuka and Nsonga in Kyangwali sub-county," Ruyonga said. He said
cholera patients are admitted at Buseruka, Butoole and Kigorobya
health units in Buseruka, Kabwooya and Kigorobya sub-counties.
"The areas hit by the pandemic are those where the majority of
residents lack toilets," Ruyonga said.
In a related development, the Kibaale District Director of Health
Services, Dr Dan Kyamanywa, said the disease had hit the sub-counties
of Mpeefu and Bwikara. He said the affected areas are the landing
sites of Ndaiga, Kabukanga and Kyaterekera in Mpeefu sub-county and
Bwikara village in Bwikara sub-county. "Cholera has so far killed 3
people including the contractor of Ndaiga Market, Muhereza
Byaruhanga," Kyamanywa said.
In Bundibugyo, 6 people are admitted at Rwebisengo Health Centre and
10 people have been reported dead. The LC3 Chairman of Rwebisengo
sub-county, Mr Assa Wamara, on 28 May 2006 said the victims are
residents of Budiba village. He attributed the outbreak of the
disease to poor sanitation.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[As can be seen on the map
(<http://www.un.org/Depts/Cartographic/map/profile/uganda.pdf>),
these 3 districts are adjacent, on the country's western border with
Congo DR and Lake Albert. - Mod.LL]
